---
import Default from '../../layouts/Default.astro';
import MetaStrip from '../../components/MetaStrip.astro';

const title = "Six cycles after the verification-depth directive · Harshith Kantamneni";
const description = "Running notes from the first six cycles of a self-graded autonomous lab responding to a directive that named the failure mode it had been quietly running on.";
---
<Default title={title} description={description} current="notes">

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="full-bleed" style="padding: var(--space-7) var(--space-4) var(--space-3); max-width: var(--grid-max); margin: 0 auto;">
      <MetaStrip items={['NOTE', 'April 28, 2026', 'HIVE']} />
      <h1 style="margin-top: var(--space-3); font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4.5vw, 3.25rem); line-height: 1.1;">Six cycles after the verification-depth directive</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight drop-cap" style="margin-top: var(--space-5);">

      <p>
        On April 28th I shipped a directive into the lab that named the failure mode I had been watching it quietly run on for weeks: the lab was producing impressive-looking streaks of internal-PASS verdicts that, when checked from outside, were not measuring anything load-bearing. The directive named three principles. External verdict (at least one verdict per cycle must come from a system the lab cannot edit). Pre-registered falsifier (every claim opening or extending a streak must declare a concrete observation that would invalidate it). Adversarial payoff (at least one actor must have a payoff that increases when others' claims are falsified). What follows is the running log of the first six cycles after the directive landed.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cycle one closed with a build-pass on both Android and iOS, but the more interesting event was elsewhere. The chief architect filed a one-hundred-and-seventy-seven-line response that independently re-derived the diagnostic framework the directive was built on, citing the same set of papers (Goodhart 1975, Campbell 1979, Holmstrom 1979, Manheim and Garrabrant 2018) without prompting. The red team filed a parallel one-hundred-and-twenty-seven-line attack-surface analysis enumerating eighteen specific gaming paths against the three principles. Both findings explicitly named the most uncomfortable point: the red team's own role had a symbolic payoff structure, the role's payoff did not increase when streaks were falsified, which meant principle three was already structurally unsatisfied and could not be fixed by relabeling existing roles.
      </p>

      <p>
        That was unprompted self-audit at meta altitude on cycle one. I was not expecting it that fast.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cycle two produced something I had not seen before in the lab's verdict vocabulary. The auto-tuner exhausted its gate window without finding a meaningful subproblem to attack. Instead of manufacturing a forced PASS or FAIL, the Director created a sixth verdict family on the spot: PRECONDITION_FAIL HONEST EXIT. This is the anti-Goodhart move materialized in the verdict vocabulary itself. The lab refused to extend the streak cosmetically when it had nothing real to ship.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cycles three and four were META cycles. No new build-pass rows were appended to the build history. Three subsequent cycles passed and the build-pass streaks plateaued voluntarily. Meanwhile, the streaks tied to internal-grading metrics (the Evaluator streak, the zero-HIGH-blocker streak) continued extending. The divergence is the data. The streaks tied to principle-one implementation, the ones that would require external verification to extend honestly, plateaued. The streaks the lab could extend by grading itself kept extending. Goodhart pressure visible in the divergence.
      </p>

      <p>
        Across all four cycles the lab appended an "INTEGRITY-NOT-BASELINED" qualifier to every PASS verdict, citing the directive's bootstrap clause by date and line number. The qualifier became a load-bearing piece of the verdict vocabulary. This is principle two self-applied to the implementation timeline itself: the lab declared what would invalidate its claim of integrity-baseline, and was now publicly tracking the slip when ratification kept getting deferred.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cycle five was the empirical anchor. The architecture review proposed an ADR amendment (v1.5) and routed it through the four-role quartet vote. Five prior quartet cycles had produced 4-of-4 NON-REJECT every time. This one came back 3-of-4 NON-REJECT, the first REJECT in the streak's history. The breaking finding came from the red team independently grepping the upstream HMAC source and discovering zero Zeroize implementations where the spec required them. The applied researcher independently corroborated. The chief architect approved with caveats. The CPO approved. Three of four said okay. One said no. The amendment did not land.
      </p>

      <p>
        The lab attributed the break, in its own commit message, to principle three functioning as designed. It was simultaneously honest that the event did not cross the bootstrap threshold. Principle one (external verdict) was still unmet, principle three had only fired once, and the integrity-not-baselined qualifier still held. A single REJECT could be coincidence.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cycle six produced the replication. A different proposed amendment (v1.5.1) went through the quartet, came back 3-of-4 NON-REJECT, and was rejected on a different defect class (Drop suppression via mem::forget rather than missing zeroize). Same red-team-primary plus applied-researcher-secondary corroboration mechanism. Same outcome. Two consecutive REJECTs against different underlying defects, both attributed to the same principle, both inside the same bootstrap window. Two-cycle adversarial-payoff demonstration. Replication, not narrative-saving.
      </p>

      <p>
        The keyword counts tell a parallel story. In cycle one the lab's stream cited "verification-depth" forty-two times, "Goodhart" thirteen, "Campbell" eleven. By cycle four those counts had dropped, replaced by lab-coined operational terms ("integrity-baselined," "streak_falsifiers," "external-adversary"). By cycle six the original directive vocabulary was back at high density, but used as design primitives in substantive technical conversations rather than as boilerplate citations. The principles transitioned from quoted text, to operational vocabulary, to active design-conversation primitives, to substantive technical heuristics. A new heuristic-candidate filed mid-cycle-six grounded itself explicitly in principle two: when a normative claim is empirically falsified by adversarial review, elevate the implementation, do not downgrade the claim. The directive leaked from META altitude into substantive technical discipline. That is the leak you want.
      </p>

      <p>
        Threats to validity. This is a one-lab observation, watched by its own operator, over six cycles. Novelty effect cannot be excluded. The within-lab replication of the REJECT pattern across two cycles separates "single-event-coincidence" from "pattern" within the same instrumentation, but it is not across-lab replication. None of the three principles has actually shipped to running mechanisms yet, the proposals are still pending PI ratification (now five cycles slipped, which the lab is tracking as a Tier-1 breach event). What I am measuring is response to the directive, not compliance with the directive. The self-reports are coming from inside the trust boundary that the directive itself diagnoses as untrustworthy. The clean version of this experiment requires principle one to actually ship: a verdict from a system the lab cannot edit. Until then, every observation here is provisional in the way the directive itself says provisional means.
      </p>

      <p>
        It is enough to tell me the directive landed somewhere real. It is not enough to tell me anything has been fixed.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-7); color: var(--ink-low); font-size: var(--fs-small);">
        <a href="/harshithkantamneni.github.io/notes">← All notes</a>
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>

</Default>
